      <Placemark>
        <name>🟣🔴150 / GBG / A Town

https://web.archive.org/web/20120427205254/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/gas-gang-gas

https://web.archive.org/web/20111229030542/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/cfr-corleone-family-riders-certified-riders

https://web.archive.org/web/20120220221334/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/peel-dem-crew-poverty-driven-children

https://web.archive.org/web/20111012054418/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/28s</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X6j9lcF7Yk9YagZhJOve-spJ2LRCc0vfOtlYIjLtZOO62L1jNpv6af1PhcY6IqEaz8cGpZuE_Y3YtcqoD2D25mrDVzKSblSIa7UY00-fLKhf6umtTtWMWSvTvR_JPSgcmb1-PmveXKnrw0flJvdPxJaoYXZPPe7E2ex1Z4bftbnIMyU0con4kGYvz1iKrVE_-XCR0c?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Lambeth, Brixton, Angell Town SW9<br><br>150, also known as 'Get Back Gang' (GBG), are a large street gang based on the Angell Town estate and the neighbouring Loughborough estate in the Brixton area, situated within the SW9 postcode. The Angell Town estate is known as 'ATown' and has a long history of gang violence.  This area has been home to some of the largest, and most well known, gangs in London including the 28s, PDC and GAS.<br><br>One of the first gangs from Angell Town were known as the 28s. The 28s membership was drawn from across Lambeth borough, most notably in Brixton, Stockwell, Clapham, Tulse Hill, and Rosendale Road. They were most active during the late 1980s and 1990s, having followed on from the 'Raiders' Gang. The original 28s formed around 1988, whilst 'Younger 28s' (Y.28s) formed in 1991 and then 'Younger Younger 28s' (YY.28s) in 1994. The 28s name came about because there was 28 original members. The gang very much commanded the attention of, and influenced local youths, specifically the those from the Angell Town estate, where following younger generations began to adopt the 28s gang name. The Brixton area was home to the Jamaican 'Yardie' drug dealing gangs from Spanish Town and Kingston. When the 28s progressed into adulthood, and begun to engage in serious drug dealing businesses of their own, tension grew between Black British born gangs and the Jamaicans over rights to drug turfs. 28s would also come in to conflict with the 'Untouchables Gang' who also had membership from Angell Town. The 28s were also known for bank and post-office robberies, often carried out in 'steaming' fashion. Like many gangs of the time there was little to identify the gangs such as colours and YouTube videos. They existed purely for their financial gain and crime whilst the identity and definers of the gangs was very much an underground subculture that evaded the media attention street gangs receive today. Whilst the gangs may have been unknown to the wider public they had amassed a significant reputation within criminal circles. 28s had been to Lambeth what the 'Peckham Boys' were to Southwark and the 'Ghetto Boys' were to Lewisham. However, unlike the latter, they did not really ever commercialise themselves through literature, local media or music videos. The Y.28s from the mid 1990s would later go on to form their own gang known as the 'Peel Dem Crew' (PDC), who were a following generation from the late 1990s and 2000s.<br><br>PDC were formed by the youths from Angell Town who had grown up looking up to the 'original' 28s, and had referred to themselves as the "Younger 28s" (Y.28s). They had began to make a name for themselves for robberies and around 1995 a youth known as "Tanna" had came up with a new name for the gang the 'Peel Dem Crew' (PDC). 'Peel Dem' is Jamaican street slang for robbing or ripping people off. Whilst "Tanna" may have came up with the gangs new name of PDC, "JaJa Soze" is probably the most well known member of PDC, and was key in bringing his connections including from 'Younger 28s', together under the PDC umbrella that grew from Angell Town to cover Brixton, Stockwell and Kennington. Like older 28s before them, the PDC gang were involved in battles with the Jamaican 'Yardie' drug gangs, which led to a continuous cycle of robberies and violence. PDC also came into conflict with 'Peckham Boys' whilst they had an 'on-off' relationships with SMS from Streatham and another Brixton gang OC who were from nearby Myatts Field estate. PDC began to split up through 2005/2006 following the deaths of three prominent PDC members, who were shot dead during 2004/2005. One of those killed was Solomon Martin known as "Blacker". The closest friends and family of "Blacker", including PDC rapper "Shak Corleone", disbanded from PDC and formed a new set known as CFR. CFR is interpreted as either 'Corleone Family Riderz' or the 'Certified Riderz', and were later adopted under the umbrella of the 031 Bloods who had been started by yet another former PDC member, "Tanna". Through close family connections (Ratlin Corleone), the 'Mozart Bloods' (HRB), in West London, are sometimes referred to as the Mozart CFR. CFR were closely linked with another street gang formed by former PDC members, known as 'Paid In Full' (PIF). PIF were primarily based around Angell Town and Loughborough and identified with the colour of purple. By 2005/2006 several of PDC elders began to move into more legitimate businesses, with their PDC acronym becoming more commonly referred to as 'Poverty Driven Children', or 'Pray Days Change' to now reflect the more positive nature of their group, or now more suitably "movement", with a focus on the music industry as an outlet for their energy.<br><br>During 2007/08 the youngest generation from Angell Town, known as the 'Y.28s' (not to be confused with the Y.28s that preceded PDC) began to form friendships with neighbouring Brixton gangs such as 'Tiny OC' from Myatts Fields and also 'Murderzone' (MZ) from Somerleyton. The Y28s and Tiny OC had inherited a fierce rivalry with the Peckham based gangs and decided that the Brixton gangs needed to unite together as one. The youngest generations from Angell Town, Myatts Field, Loughborough and Somerleyton (the four main blocks of Brixton) joined forces to form the collective known as the GAS Gang. GAS can be translated as ‘Grind And Stack’ or as ‘Guns And Shanks’ and ‘Grip And Shoot’. GAS identified with combined colours of green for Myatts Field (OC) and purple for Angell Town (Y28s). GAS began to arise noticeably from 2007/2008 and inherited a fierce rivalry with Peckham from their predecessors- OC, PDC, PIF and CFR. This fierce rivalry between Brixton and Peckham during the 2000s was one of the most reputed rivalries and fiercest wars in London at the time between some of Londons largest and most renowned gang territories. By 2010 that beef with Peckham had began to die down, whilst a new and growing rivalry with Tulse Hill (TN1) was developing. The beef with Tulse Hill brought GAS into conflicts with Stockwell (ABM) and Brixton Hill who had sided with Tulse Hill. GAS were closely affiliated with nearby Brixton gangs, most notably OC from Myatts Field and SIRU (formerly Murderzone) from Somerleyton. Members of GAS from Myatts Field repped both OC and GAS whilst members from Somerleyton repped both SIRU and GAS. GAS also had affiliations with other gangs including YRS from Brixton, 031 from Stockwell and Brooklyn from Old Kent Road area. GAS began to split up through 2013, following personal disputes, and accusations of snitching. The Angell Town, Myatts Field and Loughborough areas remained closely affiliated, leaving GAS/SIRU members from Somerleyton now ostracized from the rest of Brixton beefing with their former allies, as well as historical rivals. Those GAS members from Angell Town and Loughborough went on to form a new clique known as '150'. The founders of '150' had previously been prominent figures within GAS Gang.<br><br>150 are a direct relation to GAS and have inherited many of the same rivals and alliances as GAS. 150 would later form their own younger sets which included 'Armed & Dangerous' (AD) from the Angell Town estate and 'Cassava' (CMG) from the Loughborough estate. During the later part of the 2010s 150 members have started to refer to the gang as GBG (Get Back Gang). They are closely allied with nearby 410, 17, 031, 37, Claptown, Uptop and CMB. They beef 674, LTH, ABM, RP, Harlem, KuKu, Moscow17 and 55. Some younger members also beef with former allies SIRU.<br><br>Associated Rappers} Stickz / MDargg / M24 / Grizzy / Ard Adz / Sneakbo / S Wavey / JBoy / Tookie / Skatty / Sho Shallow / JBandz / D38 / JM / DTwins / Remaaa]]></description>
