      <Placemark>
        <name>⚫🔵Dulwich / Circle

https://web.archive.org/web/20110529192432/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/peckham-boys-black-gang</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X7OTfTzvBiY-1wRkcPSRRSzdEh-prQvuU2LyVFjEIAjIYTzK3vGu083Jbc4_sEqR11PtriYbWhT7STuvSAxEdZNA2KwzzmjisAJ2QbhWT8yasy_UgvUszrBBsFCt220_R02hgtgl_t9Nt0hR1YrtyR-GlPdsGc30_IpFb4sSc25EISCIoJ83SvZitjATR4xty0CSnA?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Southwark, Dulwich SE5/SE22<br><br>The Peckham Boys are one of the oldest and largest gangs in London and based on numerous estates in the Peckham (SE15) area, particularly North Peckham, Gloucester Grove, Willowbrook, Bells Gardens (Yellow Brick), Oliver Goldsmith, Sumner, Acorn (Wood Dene) and Southampton Way estates in Peckham. The gang are also located on estates in nearby Camberwell and Dulwich (SE5), notably Lettsom, Glebe and Dog Kennel Hill estates. The gang have also been active on estates in Walworth (SE17) notably the Aylesbury estate as well as other Peckham estates around Queens road notably Cossall, Clifton and Wood Dene estates.<br><br>The first generation of Peckham Boys during the 1970s and 1980s mainly took their names from local Peckham estates with names like 'Acorn Boys', 'North Peckham Boys', 'Yellow Brick Massive', 'Peckham Grove Boys', 'Night Jackyls' or the 'Outlaws Crew'. The gangs had recruited their own younger generations who took on the same gang name preceded by the word Young or Younger such as 'Young North Peckham Boys' and 'Young Peckham Grove Boys'.<br><br>The following generation of gang members went on to take up different names during the 1990s, some were Jamaican or Black British, whilst others were African, mainly Nigerian. Although these gangs were often referred to collectively as the ‘Peckham Boys’ these gangs younger generations were more clearly distinguishable from one another as they took on new gang names and territories. The Peckham gangs of the 1990s had been the 'Firehouse Crew', 'Gloucester Boys', 'Spanglers', 'Sunrise Crew' and the 'Younger Peckham Boys', amongst others.<br><br>By the early 2000s, the Peckham Boys had consolidated as a single gang and their sets were structured by age into the 'Peckham Boys' (PB), the 'Younger Peckham Boys' (YPB), or the 'Younger Younger Peckham Boys' (YYPB) and 'Peckham Kids' (PK). The Peckham Boys had continued to be affiliated with their predecessors in the 'Firehouse Crew' and 'Younger Firehouse Crew' while 'Younger Peckham Boys' were closely linked with the Dulwich Boys/Circle Crew from Denmark Hill, Champion Hill and Dog Kennel Hill estates, in Dulwich. Their gangs affiliation with Dulwich was built through "Archbishop Michael Ramsey School" where they had all attended school together. PK, YYPB and YPB, combined would number in the hundreds and be quite flexible. Older 'Peckham Boys' would be much smaller in number, although more solid composed of career criminals in charge of the younger generations.<br><br>Following conflict within the 'Peckham Boys' sets during the early 2000s, the names of the 'Peckham Boys' sets began to change in the mid 2000s. This tied in with a period when the street gangs became far more noticeable publicly from their efforts to become rappers. Many of the gang names across London doubled up as music crew names and YouTube and MySpace then became the social arenas to support aspiring artists. The new names were more menacing acronyms that could be translated into different meanings. 'Peckham Boys' became known as SN1 (Spare-No-1), the 'Younger Peckham Boys' became SI (Shoot Instant) while the 'Younger Younger Peckham Boys' became PYG (Peckham Young Gunners). At this time gang definers, and identity, became important and the 'Peckham Boys' began associating with the colour black wearing black bandanas and reference to Southwark as the "Black Borough", whilst 'Peckham Boys' gang became better known as the 'Black Gang', or 'Black Gang Ryders'. Peckham was also given the nickname of 'Pecknarm' in a reference to Vietnam and the perceived notion that their area was a high-crime war-zone of sorts. In 2008 their SI (Shoot Instant) set split into two factions. Those based on the Aylesbury estate (SE17) remained with the SI (Shoot Instant) name, where as some SI members, based around the main Peckham (SE15) estates formed a new set known as OPB (Original Peckham Boys). Both would remain closely affiliated.<br><br>'Peckham Boys' sets main rivalry has been with gangs from nearby areas, such as New Cross, Deptford and Brixton. The rivalries between 'Peckham Boys' and 'Ghetto Boys' was one of the longest running, and most renowned, gang rivalries in London from the 1990s and 2000s. The 'Peckham Boys' and 'Ghetto Boys' were two of the largest street gangs in London and that rivalry was very much Southwark versus Lewisham boroughs as the 'Peckham Boys' had influence over most of Southwark, and 'Ghetto Boys' over much of Lewisham. After many internal divisions within the 'Ghetto Boys' the decades long 'Peckham' and 'Ghetto' rivalry had ceased around 2009, ending one of the oldest, and most reputed, gang rivalries in London. By late 2007/2008 the main rival of 'Peckham Boys' had become Brixton gangs. Older Peckham cliques like SN1 and OPB had beef with the older Brixton generation, such as PDC, CFR and RSG, whilst the youngest Peckham sets, such as SI and PYG, had a fierce rivalry with the youngest Brixton generation, consisting of OC, GAS, SIRU and YRS. 'Peckham Boys' of this era also came into conflicts with Brixtons allies 031 from Stockwell, and Brooklyn from Old Kent Road. Their rivalry with Brixton was played out through a number of diss tracks and music videos from well known rappers from both areas. The main allies of the 'Peckham Boys' sets are gangs from nearby Walworth (SE17), and Camberwell and Dulwich (SE5) Members from these areas would roll together as one often under the banner of the 'Peckham Boys'<br><br>Through 2010 there was a split within some 'Peckham Boys' sets, involving the 'Peckham Boys' from the Lettsom estate, in Camberwell (SE5). There had been growing rifts between senior members from Lettsom and members from the main Peckham estates which started around 2008, but grew over time escalating into the Peckham civil war during 2010. The members from Lettsom estate split from original 'Peckham Boys' sets (SN1/OPB/SI/PYG), and formed the 'Lettsom G's', whilst the remaining PYG members had changed their name to 'Anti'. This gang would roll closely with another 'Peckham Boys' set known as 'GMG', and together they became known as 'Anti/GMG'. 'Anti/GMG' were active in the fierce beef with Lettsom, and started to beef with 'Peckham Boys' based on Pelican estate known as 'Crane Block'. Some PYG members formed a new set known as 'Breadset'.<br><br>In 2010/2011 a new younger Peckham set began to emerge known as 'Peckham Kidz' (PK). This gangs main rivalry was with the new younger generations from Brixton, although by this time the Peckham versus Brixton beef had began to die down with the oldest Peckham generations being torn apart by internal conflicts. By 2013/14 a younger generation to PK had began to form known as '365' and '365/DankBoys'. '365' would form the nucleus of 'Zone 2', who have been the main younger generation of the 'Peckham Boys' since 2015/2016. 'Zone 2', like older Peckham sets, had originally been closely affiliated with nearby Walworth, but by 2016 the relationship between the Peckham and Walworth areas and the Brandon estate in particular have became more contentious with the two areas now in serious conflict. The main beef is between 'Zone 2' and 'Moscow17' from Brandon estate although they come into conflict with the Aylesbury estate (AY17) and the Browning estate (Browning17) as well, and also 'Moscow17' allies 'Harlem', from Kennington. Another younger Peckham set who are closely affiliated with 'Zone 2' are known as the 'Younger Peckham Boys' (YPB) reviving the older YPB name which had been around in the 1990s and early 2000s. Much of the older generation who had been beefing have began to reconcile with Lettsom estate and Peckham linked up again]]></description>
