      <Placemark>
        <name>🔘🔵Turnham / RTT / FNF

https://web.archive.org/web/20111012182055/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/brockley-mandem</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X5SDV4Vjp4dsCNlDgqhQF--Neyjb_oLP3QQFJ-mGfyB4yXBcELC7ypoOf0j4-WVlInAu239Y9TOJAg5jDrGQ-8a_sevWSBmDmQYSzX3UW_JrfTWymHyL1c9B8fOquWxhbp5rYeYBjncHKBs4Dojz1ikMa9g0anIJ7Y5AR_qAwITqo5owa3Mn4DBRQwWP-toSgPW9Rg?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Lewisham, Brockley SE4<br><br>Brockley Mandem have been in active since the early 1990s on the Honor Oak estate,  often commonly known locally as Turnham estate. They were closely affiliated with the Ghetto Boys from New Cross, Deptford and Lewisham. The second generation of Brockley Mandem were the 'Younger Brockley Man' (YBM). YBM used to be close allies to the Ghetto Boys, and together they often fought against their rivals Peckham Boys, Woolwich Boys, and the Penge gangs. Feuds between YBM and the Ghetto Boys particularly Deptford Ghetto Boys meant that the close relationship became more contentious over time.  This was owing to Deptford Ghetto Boys causing problems in Brockley, with personal disputes between older members of both areas whilst in prison.  YBM, from then on tended to only associate with the Ghetto Boys factions from the New Cross, Catford and Lewisham areas of the borough<br><br>Brockley, particularly the Turnham estate, has a long history of gangs, and organised crime. Initially under rule of British and Irish criminals,  the area later became more associated with Caribbean criminals in the 1990s, before the rise of the present-day gangs. It was not until late 1990s media began to acknowledge the street gang, referred to as the ‘Brockley Boys’ in 1999, describing the rivalry with nearby gangs from nearby Peckham and Penge. Brockley was just one of many areas of Lewisham that was renowned for drug dealing and a thriving drug market. As the crack market in London grew in the 1990s and the early 2000s crack houses would begin popping up in many gang territories, often under the control of Jamaican 'Yardie' crews. Links were established between Brockley and gangs in Bristol, Miami, New York and parts of Jamaica. Although the young Brockley gang members have frequently participated in violence and committed robberies media attention was limited compared with the Ghetto Boys<br><br>By the late 2000s the younger generation from the Turnham estate began to identify with the colour grey and referred to as 'Turnham Young Bucks' (TYB), and also "Team Brockley". During this period they had formed a close alliance with SG from Grove Park. Both had a fierce rivalry with 'Anti Shower' from nearby Catford and 'Black Mafia' from Lewisham. The current generation of the 'Turnham' gang are also known as AR (Armed Response) or simply 'Turnham'. They are loosely allied with BSide, Block 6, Block 12, 150 and 410. They beef with SG, M20, Monson, 674 and LTH.<br><br>The 'AR' gang is now extinct and the youngers now go by RTT or FNF. RTT/FNF are allied with 4Anti, BSide and GMD. They beef LDG/BlueHillz, 6thStreet, Block 6, Ghetto, PR15, T1D, M20, SG, Lovelinch, Monson, DQN and JRoad.<br><br>Associated Rappers} Remington / M3 / Drilla ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#poly-757575-2701-77</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value><![CDATA[https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X5SDV4Vjp4dsCNlDgqhQF--Neyjb_oLP3QQFJ-mGfyB4yXBcELC7ypoOf0j4-WVlInAu239Y9TOJAg5jDrGQ-8a_sevWSBmDmQYSzX3UW_JrfTWymHyL1c9B8fOquWxhbp5rYeYBjncHKBs4Dojz1ikMa9g0anIJ7Y5AR_qAwITqo5owa3Mn4DBRQwWP-toSgPW9Rg?authuser=0&fife=s16383]]></value>
          </Data>
