      <Placemark>
        <name>🟡37 / OJB

https://web.archive.org/web/20120102212030/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/stick-em-up-kids-suk</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X4xJH_9RLsX-elmCVA7r1Zyde4x1eLSXPZ_s3jexK4R5vzNobMOIgvtJoT1Aiw2iHo0TEbgTdKGpfaaXIB1BuwfiTsp5VNbQtTTWpk6qEG4lS7idvlaD8fMcDY_qH1UnYHEQthbeCO_SfY4vXd9oGnaf-Zuf-QIHypc4LZkmLTW-VC_zekOw3gd5uWe3pwE4IGHFS4?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Wandsworth, Clapham Junction and Battersea SW11<br><br>37 are a large street gang who are based within the borough of Wandsworth in the areas of Battersea, Clapham Junction Wandsworth, Roehampton and Southfields, which cover the SW11, SW15, SW18 and SW19 postcodes. The '37' gang are mostly active on Winstanley, York Road, Badric Court, Surrey Lane, Kambala, Doddington and Rollo, Maysoule, Ethelburga and Battersea Park estates which are around Battersea and Clapham Junction. The other prominent estates include the Arndale and Wendlesworth estates in Wandsworth and also the Alton estate in Roehampton, as well as Southfields area estates, including Southmead and Edgecombe Hall estates. '37' used to be known as SUK (Stick'em Up Kids). As the old SUK name began to fall out of use during the mid 2010s the gang became more commonly known as '37'. <br><br>SUK had formed around 2004 as a younger generation to an old gang known as the 'Junction Boys'. 'Junction Boys' were most active from the 1980s to the end of the 1990s and had been in 'on-off' conflicts with the 28's gang from Brixton and the 'Peckham Boys', but had also came into conflict with the gangs based in Hammersmith & Fulham, West London. The 'Junction Boys' held an influence over much of Wandsworth, and had members throughout the borough, extending as far as Putney and Roehampton areas,  although 'Junction Boys' were most active on local estates surrounding Queenstown Road areas, Battersea, Clapham Junction, and nearby areas of Vauxhaul. By 2000 the 'Junction Boys' name had died out and there was no real name for the gang from the Battersea area between 2000 and 2004, when the SUK generation had formed. SUK had identified with the colour yellow, as do the present 37 generations. SUK also had a younger generation under their wing known as 'Surrey Lane Soldiers' (SLS) from the Surrey Lane estate in Battersea.<br><br>37 consists of several smaller affiliated sets located across the borough. These sets combined form the larger '37' gang alliance.  The largest, and the most well known of these, are OJB (Official Junction Boyz) from the Winstanley estate and surrounding estates in the Battersea and Clapham Junction area. The other sets include 'Block 10' who are mainly active on both the Arndale estate and Wendlesworth estate, within the Wandsworth area and RR (Road to Riches) based on the Alton estate in Roehampton. '37' are allied with 150, 410, 17, 031, Claptown and Uptop as well as Mozart in West London. '37' beef with 417, 674, 55, LTH, ABM, Mitcham, Pollards Hill, Harlem and KuKu.<br><br>Associated Rappers} Skeamer / Skore Beezy / Burner / Sai So / Clue / Wrecker]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#poly-FFEA00-2501-77</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value><![CDATA[https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X4xJH_9RLsX-elmCVA7r1Zyde4x1eLSXPZ_s3jexK4R5vzNobMOIgvtJoT1Aiw2iHo0TEbgTdKGpfaaXIB1BuwfiTsp5VNbQtTTWpk6qEG4lS7idvlaD8fMcDY_qH1UnYHEQthbeCO_SfY4vXd9oGnaf-Zuf-QIHypc4LZkmLTW-VC_zekOw3gd5uWe3pwE4IGHFS4?authuser=0&fife=s16383]]></value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
        <Polygon>
