      <Placemark>
        <name>🟢GS28 / T-Block / Block Gang

https://web.archive.org/web/20120411214601/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/south-london-gangs/t--block-original-greenside-bangers</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X7RxPqCMJiWF46JJACUgjJpFHYIgyPKNGM8xbzopwJDw8Xe5L6aNN93plf9GW2lhemDNFpBYMdR1e8IgQjJ8WPQUUpzMpqxHsAy3j8lESqKZdIsDvWZeHaXt4qSlNZTFIbpQlGcfEEdVl1TkEBMVgzULEt4Zbc87qMIK-zoYCoPs5zanENiH9ansgNdhCSdwMkIwC4?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Greenwich, Thamesmead SE28<br><br>The Thamesmead estate was built on drained marshland on the south bank of the River Thames in the 1960s and 1970s straddling the boroughs of Bexley and Greenwich, within the SE28 postcode. The estate would become home to working class families from the south of the river Thames, rehoused as a result of the slum clearance in areas of Southwark and Deptford. Thamesmead estate was initially a predominantly white area, although a smaller number of black families had also moved into the area. This contrasted with neighbouring Woolwich, where many black and Asian families were being rehoused. This post war resettlement would coincide with a breakup of many notorious crime families like the Krays and Richardsons. This vacuum was filled by local criminals from particular families who made money from 'armed robberies', 'hijacking lorries' and 'protection rackets'. By the early 1990s these families had moved into the drugs trade, and began to rake in the profits.<br><br>By the late 1980s rival, or rather competing, local gangs had began to form in the area, including 'The Krays' from Eltham and 'The Firm' from Thamesmead. Both groups consisted of predominantly white males, and had shared values inherited from those old crime families, including sexist, homophobic and racist attitudes. At the centre of those gangs were sons of certain criminals involved in the drug trade. They differed from the older generations in their general recklessness and unpredictability, with a tendency to carry knives. Both gangs would come together if threatened by the multi-racial gangs of nearby Woolwich. The rivalry between the white youths of the 'Thamesmead' and 'Eltham' street gangs on the one side and multiracial Woolwich gangs on the other, inevitably took on a racist dimension. Both 'Thamesmead' and 'Eltham' had widened this out to encompass any Black and Asian person they came across, regardless of whether they even had any involvement in youth gangs. There were some exceptions to the generally white make-up of the 'Thamesmead Firm'. One of their group was from one of the few black families on the estate and he was made an exception having grown up with and was intimately known to other members of 'The Firm'.<br><br>Under 'The Firm' there were several 'junior' street gangs that had served as proving grounds for youngsters keen to make their names. They had names such as 'the Goldfish Gang' or the Nutty (or Nazi) Turnouts (often known as the NTOs), 'the Rudds' and 'the Tenches'. The 'Thamesmead Firm' and rivals 'Eltham Krays' were both regularly committing racist attacks on black and asian youths in Eltham and Thamesmead, and now somewhat competing against each other. Amongst the long list of victims knifed by both the gangs during the peak of their activities during the early 1990s were a young Asian lad, 'Rohit Duggal', stabbed to death outside a kebab shop in Tudor Parade on Well Hall Road, and two teens killed simply for being black. These were 'Rolan Adams', murdered by the members of the 'Firm' in the February of 1991, and 'Stephen Lawrence', murdered by the 'Eltham Krays' in April 1993.<br><br>By the 2000s the demographics of the estate had began to change with many African families many of Nigerian origin settling on the Thamesmead estate.  During this period the new generation, known as T-Block/Block Gang, would form. They are now the second oldest gang in Greenwich, having outlasted several other street gangs around Thamesmead, many of which dissipated through conflicts with them such as the 'Mad Souljaz' and 'Abbey Wood Boys'. Some of them later became incorporated into the gang. From 2001 - 2008 the gang was known as 'T-Block', and was made up of local young Nigerian males. Their oldest generations of the gang were loosely affiliated with 'Peckham Boys' sets, owing to a fact that many Nigerians moved to Thamesmead during the re generation of the North Peckham estate. When Tulse Hill began to call themselves 'T-Block',  the Thamesmead gangs changed their name to 'Block Gang', also known as 'Original Block Gang' and 'Original Greenside Bangers' (OGB). During the late 2000s and the early 2010s they had a set known as 'Hustling Brings Gwop'/'Handle Bare Guns' (HBG). The area is also a home to Nigerian organised '419' organised gangs (419 being the Nigerian penal code for fraud) and has been a hotspot for fraud associated with Nigerian criminal gangs with Thamesmead once being dubbed “Little Lagos”. 'Block Gang' are affiliated with the 'Ferrier Boys', and together they identify with the colour of green referring to their territory of Thamesmead, and Kidrooke / Eltham area, as “Green Town". During the 2000s, and into early 2010s they were in conflict with the 'Woolwich Boys' and 'Cherry Boys', as well as white gangs from nearby Abbey Wood and Bexley, notably the RA and YRA (Racist Attack / Young Racist Attack) gangs. Their current generation are known as GS28. Their GS28 name is taken from 'Greenside' (GS) and the number '28' taken from the SE28 postcode. The GS28 gang are allied with Parkside and Ferrier. They beef with WoolyO, Cherry and AWB.<br><br>Associated Rappers} Goose / Frecks]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#poly-097138-2701-77</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value><![CDATA[https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X7RxPqCMJiWF46JJACUgjJpFHYIgyPKNGM8xbzopwJDw8Xe5L6aNN93plf9GW2lhemDNFpBYMdR1e8IgQjJ8WPQUUpzMpqxHsAy3j8lESqKZdIsDvWZeHaXt4qSlNZTFIbpQlGcfEEdVl1TkEBMVgzULEt4Zbc87qMIK-zoYCoPs5zanENiH9ansgNdhCSdwMkIwC4?authuser=0&fife=s16383]]></value>
