    <Folder>
      <name>NorthWest London</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>🔴Press Road (PRS)

https://web.archive.org/web/20111231193226/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/northwest-london-gangs/press-road-crew</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X5447tVyxtMJgCA9ecLIXO41Ui7k3nXwDn3So6E-ncYGPCeRnUMNB9HCL2LAMIFf5vnSz-BFSYNN5Qx4xzH_R6XlLBL3sKrlvB2v1TiYFsgKqrGGukOU1VnaFYiKDQqzoP3HUPZQcWGFTfp_hfUL81fweyiU2xyznDOUCbnd8rm-i47J-HCjZ2MviaJ88DGhSyzvfM?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Brent, Neasden NW10<br><br>The Press Road Soldiers (PRS) are a small street gang who are based around Press Road in Neasden, within the NW10 postcode.  The gang formed in the late 1990s as the 'Press Road Crew' (PRC).<br><br>The gangs roots can be traced back to the days of the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) who were a Jamaican yardie gang who had been active in the late 1990s and early 2000s. Most of their members came from Harlesden and Stonebridge as well as other areas of northwest London such as Kilburn, Willesden, Neasden, Wembley and Kensal Green.  They organised their activities from their main bases of "Stonebridge Community Centre", just off Hillside on Stonebridge estate and the "Elm Tree" and "Palm Shade" pubs, in Harlesden. 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) were lead by "notorious" Jamaican "Yardie" gangsters which included figures including [Winston "Escobar" Harris], [Stephen "Beamer" Murray],   [Jermaine "My Lord" Hamilton], [Rudolf "Rudy" King],  [Ricky "Diney" Sweeney], [Dean "Bobby" Roberts] and [Tyrone "Lofty" Freckleton], the older brother of Church Road rapper "Nines" and the deceased Church Road member Wayne "Zino" Freckleton. Winston "Escobar" Harris had been arrested and charged multiple times for a plethora of drug offences in Queens, New York City, before he fled to London, settling in Harlesden. Other Jamaican drug dealers would join him, some directly from Jamaica and also others from the USA and formed the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) around 1995.  Some 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) members had close ties with 'Tottenham Mandem' (TMD) particularly their infamous leader Mark Lambie. The 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) were known for the rivalry with 'Mus Luv Crew' (MLC) from Kensal Green and part of the deadly conflict triangle which encompassed an area from Stonebridge, Harlesden, Willesden and Kensal Green between 1997 and 2004. From 1997/98 onwards and especially following the death of a LCC leader Rudolf "Rudy" King, the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) began to split. Rudolf "Rudy" King was a leading member of the Church Road faction and was rumored to have been killed by a fellow 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) member. After his death the Church Road faction lead by both Dean "Bobby" Roberts and Tyrone "Lofty" Freckleton started to war with the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC), which is what has caused the longstanding feud between Stonebridge and Church Road, which has since been inherited by the younger following generations from both areas since the early 2000s onwards. The break up of "Yardie" gangs, such as 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) lead to the creation of the present day gangs in North West London in the early 2000s, notably Stonebridge, Church Road, Press Road, St Raphs, Kensal Green, Chalkhill and Kingsbury.<br><br>Members of the 'Press Road Crew' were high ranking figures in the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) and were heavily involved in the conflict with the Church Road members, which has resulted in the Press Road and Church Road areas being in a conflict ever since. During the 1990s and the 2000s Press Road had a fearsome reputation despite being only a small area. They had close links with Kingsbury and Kensal Green,  as well as Tottenham Mandem (TMD). During the late 1990s and early 2000s the Press Road Crew, and their allies Kingsbury, were were known to operate on nearby estates, such as Chalkhill and Grahame Park causing serious conflicts between Press Road and those areas. In 2003 several younger members of the gang were given the UK's first ever mass ASBO, banning them from the Chalkhill estate area. Around 2007/2008 the younger generation from Press Road become known as the Press Road Soldiers (PRS) and were closely affiliated with a group known as STA9 who were also active in the Wembley and Cricklewood areas. Press Road are allied with St Raphs, Wembley Fornia Dons, Kingsbury, Mozart, Kensal Green and North Kilburn. They beef with Chalkhill, Stonebridge, Monks Park, A9, South Kilburn and Church Road.<br><br>Associated Rappers} T.E.K.S / TS]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#poly-FF5252-2701-120</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value><![CDATA[https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X5447tVyxtMJgCA9ecLIXO41Ui7k3nXwDn3So6E-ncYGPCeRnUMNB9HCL2LAMIFf5vnSz-BFSYNN5Qx4xzH_R6XlLBL3sKrlvB2v1TiYFsgKqrGGukOU1VnaFYiKDQqzoP3HUPZQcWGFTfp_hfUL81fweyiU2xyznDOUCbnd8rm-i47J-HCjZ2MviaJ88DGhSyzvfM?authuser=0&fife=s16383]]></value>
          </Data>
