      <Placemark>
        <name>🔴St Raphs (SRS)

https://web.archive.org/web/20120103041921/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/northwest-london-gangs/st-raphz-soldiers-srs</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X5S166MyhKBEw4yu9Xy3kY9mV-GaNUn2PAQBDO0NGWbN_JbLTTSTBTiV54p5P0Lu1gfpTo8XvxjphTmnYzEvXv78Do3iALHChXnTHozyNsd8oI8DsHlpazoWFp6B2Md1We2IXEW-Oq7I1y8CMJ59kfqJEoJ2Yn0IeFt8wGvPdy_kiRFLilzK8TQFrfsHreu7tJZAwQ?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Brent, Neasden NW10<br><br>St Raphs Soldiers (SRS) are a street gang who are based on the St Raphaels estate located in Neasden, within the NW10 postcode. The gang was formed in the early 2000s and they would later go on to identify as Bloods. St Raphs estate had formed part of the 'SMG' Bloods alliance which consisted of members from St Raphs, Mozart and Kensal Green.<br><br>The gangs roots can be traced back to the days of the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) who were a Jamaican yardie gang who had been active in the late 1990s and early 2000s. Most of their members came from Harlesden and Stonebridge as well as other areas of northwest London such as Kilburn, Willesden, Neasden, Wembley and Kensal Green.  They organised their activities from their main bases of "Stonebridge Community Centre", just off Hillside on Stonebridge estate and the "Elm Tree" and "Palm Shade" pubs, in Harlesden. 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) were lead by "notorious" Jamaican "Yardie" gangsters which included figures including [Winston "Escobar" Harris], [Stephen "Beamer" Murray],  [Jermaine "My Lord" Hamilton], [Rudolf "Rudy" King],  [Ricky "Diney" Sweeney], [Dean "Bobby" Roberts] and [Tyrone "Lofty" Freckleton], the older brother of Church Road rapper "Nines" and the deceased Church Road member Wayne "Zino" Freckleton. Winston "Escobar" Harris had been arrested and charged multiple times for a plethora of drug offences in Queens, New York City, before he fled to London, settling in Harlesden. Other Jamaican drug dealers would join him, some directly from Jamaica and also others from the USA and formed the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) around 1995.  Some 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) members had close ties with 'Tottenham Mandem' (TMD) particularly their infamous leader Mark Lambie. The 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) were known for the rivalry with 'Mus Luv Crew' (MLC) from Kensal Green and part of the deadly conflict triangle which encompassed an area from Stonebridge, Harlesden, Willesden and Kensal Green between 1997 and 2004. From 1997/98 onwards and especially following the death of a LCC leader Rudolf "Rudy" King, the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) began to split. Rudolf "Rudy" King was a leading member of the Church Road faction and was rumored to have been killed by a fellow 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) member. After his death the Church Road faction lead by both Dean "Bobby" Roberts and Tyrone "Lofty" Freckleton started to war with the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC), which is what has caused the longstanding feud between Stonebridge and Church Road, which has since been inherited by the younger following generations from both areas since the early 2000s onwards. The break up of "Yardie" gangs, such as 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) lead to the creation of the present day gangs in North West London in the early 2000s, notably Stonebridge, Church Road, Press Road, St Raphs, Kensal Green, Chalkhill and Kingsbury.<br><br>Following on from the Jamaican 'yardie' gangs like the 'Lock City Crew' (LCC) in the early 2000s, the younger generations from estates like St Raphs formed their own gangs, and the modern day alliances and rivalries would soon begin to take shape during the early 2000s.  The 'St Raphs Soldiers' (SRS) formed around 2003. They identified as Bloods, and formed part of the 'SMG' Bloods movement along with allies Mozart and Kensal Green. The 'SMG' name comes from the "S" in St Raphs, the "M" in Mozart and the "G" in Kensal Green. Raphs also had ties with leading figures from areas like Tottenham and Brixton. They are close allies with Mozart, Kensal Green, Church Road, Press Road, Kingsbury,  Wembley Fornia Dons and North Kilburn. They beef the Stonebridge, South Kilburn, Chalkhill, Monks Park and Lisson Green areas.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#poly-FF5252-2801-120</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value><![CDATA[https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X5S166MyhKBEw4yu9Xy3kY9mV-GaNUn2PAQBDO0NGWbN_JbLTTSTBTiV54p5P0Lu1gfpTo8XvxjphTmnYzEvXv78Do3iALHChXnTHozyNsd8oI8DsHlpazoWFp6B2Md1We2IXEW-Oq7I1y8CMJ59kfqJEoJ2Yn0IeFt8wGvPdy_kiRFLilzK8TQFrfsHreu7tJZAwQ?authuser=0&fife=s16383]]></value>
          </Data>
