      <Placemark>
        <name>🟢Lisson Green (LG8)

https://web.archive.org/web/20111019104212/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/northwest-london-gangs/lisson-green-mandem

https://web.archive.org/web/20120424142617/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/northwest-london-gangs/bengali-green-manz</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X5-qGkCOsEdTj4nkvYcHhMtL1IK06q6TxoA1ykGbJsQr1SMqkmhgJRrTndIt-mL4lOTsFrH-59tPZPFlXqY_dR9JntXdmBFc2QvRB0NuocFidQBY4oBhs6rknZxNNsWMKw9ClbCD8tL0t_8FJwDfwDOHyYyDErAZgboFx_o2vGpORkgaorDAw2_uo_CXf6pKYw-TDc?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>City of Westminster, Lisson Grove NW8<br><br>The Lisson Green Mandem (LGM) are a street gang who are based around Lisson Grove and Edgware Road area located within the NW8 postcode.  Their main territory is the Lisson Green estate,  although they are also active on the Lilestone, Fisherton, Church Street, Wharncliffe Gardens, Hall Park and Blanford Square estates. They also draw members from the Barrow Hill and Townshend estates which are located in the nearby St Johns Wood area.  Lisson Green Mandem formed in the early 1990s and were later sub-divided by age into the 'Older Green Manz' (OGM) and 'Younger Green Manz' (YGM) They are known to identify with the colour green. The Lisson Green Mandem are also known as Green Man Family (GMF), G-Team and LG8.  They are affiliated with a number of other small gangs active in the area such as 'Bengali Green Manz' (BGM),  'Edgware Road Boyz' (ERB) and 'Congolese Section' (CS), and are also allied with Ladbroke Grove, South Kilburn and Stonebridge. Their main rivals are Warwick and Mozart, but they also beef with Swiss Cottage, Cricklewood, Kensal Green and St Raphs.<br><br>Bengali Green Manz (BGM) have been active since the 1980s and are one of several Asian gangs that arose out of conflict with racist white gangs from nearby Church Street and across Regents Park (area where white 'Somers Town Boys' for many years fought against the Bengali 'Drummond Street Posse'). Younger members of the gang by the late 1990s going into the Millennium were fighting against other Asian's from parts of W/NW London in Brent, this stemming from rivalries between schools. In 1996 feuds and knife fights between rival Bengali gangs in the area caused concerns amongst police and government politicians alike. Many of the youths involved were attendees of North Westminster Community School. At the time they were worried of a growing gang culture as rivals from Lisson Green, Harrow Road, Brick Lane and Drummond Street frequently clashed. In 1996, 25% of North Westminster Community School was made up of Bengali students. BGM are most infamous for their involvement in the murder of 18-year-old teenager Jevon Henry in January 2007. Just 24 hours after he was stabbed to death the killers were on a plane to Bangladesh. Muhid Abdul, 24, also known as Posh, was making £2,000 a week dealing cocaine and cannabis. He later became involved in a dispute with Jevon’s friend David Joseph, 23, who had tried to extort money from him. David Joseph had been the intended target of the BGM members on the night of the murder, Jevon had been dropped off on the estate by Joseph to purchase some drugs in what was described as a set up or ambush. He was hit on the head with a hammer and received a single stab wound which penetrated his heart, it was meant to be Joseph that died not Jevon.]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#poly-7CB342-2501-77</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
