      <Placemark>
        <name>Drummond Street Posse (DSP)

https://web.archive.org/web/20120229003219/http://sites.google.com/site/londonstreetgangs/gang-lists/northwest-london-gangs/drummond-street-posse</name>
        <description><![CDATA[London Borough of Camden, Euston NW1<br><br>Drummond Street Posse (DSP) are a Bengali Street gang located around Drummond Street in Euston, drawing members from estates in the south of Camden including Regents Park, Cumberland Market, Ampthill and Somers Town.<br><br>In the 1950s and 1960s a Bengali community began to grow and establish itself around the Euston Road. The Euston Road area, surrounded by Drummond Street, Somers Town, Regents Park and Cromer Street, has since been affected by racial tensions between the white, Black and Asian communities. To begin with, it was predominantly the Asian population who suffered attacks from mainly white youths although sometimes joined by black youths. The youth gangs developed amidst growing racial tensions and attacks, which by the 1980s were reportedly occurring at a rate of around 200 a year against Asian residents alone in Camden. Confrontations between white and Asian youths back then were occurring on a weekly basis.<br><br>As tensions grew, the Bengali youths grouped together to protect themselves from the predominantly white 'Regents Park' and 'Somers Town' gangs, protecting their area around Drummond Street. According to some of those involved, the fights became less about racial tensions and more about violence and gang rivalries. Drummond Street was the scene for regular attacks on Bengali youths by white youths. Despite the attraction for violence, Drummond Street was prosperous looking and strewn with halal butchers and restaurants, although just a stones throw away the estates surrounding Cumberland Market and Chalton Street were very much deprived and suffering from social malaise.<br><br>With time and a shifting population that saw increased diversity, a trend began to develop which had been seen amongst Bengali youth gangs in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets. Rather than being in existence for protection, the Bengali gangs began to appear as the aggressors just as much as the white gangs. By the 1990s the violence became more frequent, more casual and allegedly more serious. With growing unemployment, in an area home to some of London's most deprived estates, the added component of a rife red light district, street prostitution and heroin - the Euston Road area became a highly contested drugs market for young men. Therefore violence between gangs in some cases was perceived to be more about control rather than racial differences, or brought on by disputes over drug money and robberies.<br><br>In 1994 15-year-old Richard Everitt, described as a harmless schoolboy, was stabbed to death by a group of Asian youths as he walked with his friend on one of the Somers Town estates. The murder was followed by a series of attacks which saw several white youths stabbed by Asian youths in the area. The murder was a tragic case of mistaken identity. Tensions had been high within the Asian community due to constant victimisation, and by the time of the murder the Drummond Street gang had been pushed to the edge. They would have settled for any white youth to attack. The Bengali boys who usually would hang around the Surma Community Centre (the whites around the Lithgow Boys Club) seemed to disappear in the days following the murder, tensions were running extremely high. The school holidays also seemed to mark the beginning of annual violence between white and Asian youths, the majority residing in the Regents Park and Somers Town areas. By the mid-1990's reports of race attacks were still ever increasing, what was astonishing however, is that white people reported only 7 racial attacks, although it was common knowledge that Asians were by now also responsible for attacks on a regular basis.Seeking retribution a month after the murder, a gang of white youths ambushed a van of Bengali youths and began hurling missiles on Crowndale Road. It later was reported that the murder had been in revenge for two Bengali youths who had been beaten and robbed on a local estate. Ricky Everitt was an innocent victim and sad case of mistaken identity, it had been another youth, Liam Coyle, who was being sought that day for reprisal. There was a marked escalation in gang-related violence on both sides of the ethnic divide involving many of the youths who attended the South Camden Community School. In those days it was considered an act of provocation if white gangs crossed into Drummond Street, however, a row of Asian shops along Chalton Street later became a new frontline for racist attacks.<br><br>The two dominant gangs, Drummond Street Posse (Asian) and the Somers Town Boys (white) fought continously amongst one another for many years, even still to this day. In 1999, police recorded 126 gang fights between the two groups alone. As well as fighting pitched battles, the Drummond Street Posse by the late 1990's and early 2000's were also in conflict with other Bengali street gangs, one a newer gang a short distance down the Euston Road, known as Cromer Street Massive, and also the well established Brick Lane Massive from the other side of London. The conflict with Brick Lane had allegedly begun following a confrontation actually on Brick Lane itself, the epicentre of London's Bengali community. It emerged that during the conflicts gang members from Drummond Street Posse were driving over to Brick Lane, kidnapping rival gang members and bringing them back to Camden where they would be beaten. This occurred on numerous occasions throughout the 1990’s and even into the millennium.Other pitched battles involving Drummond Street against local rivals Cromer Street occurred frequently throughout 2003, literally on a weekly basis, to which the threat of long custodial sentences were being directed at gang members by judges.<br><br>Over the last few years, whilst conflict in the area has still ensued, attention has moved away from the white and Bengali groups and onto the more ethnically diverse gangs further north of the borough. Since 2003, there has been relatively little attention paid to the gangs surrounding Euston Road. Their only recent mention in the media had been for a series of seasonal dispersal zones and curfews implemented by police and council in attempts to curb anti-social behaviour and youth violence in the area.Drummond Street membership and use of the name Drummond Street Posse has declined in recent years, as has conflict with other nearby Bengali areas. There are now closer more organised links between various Bengali gangs in north-west London (i.e. Camden, Chalton Street, Cromer Street), and extending to other areas with significant Bengali populations (both within and outside of London). Some of this relates to the retail distribution of heroin and crack-cocaine with finance becoming a primary motivator.]]></description>
