        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://mymaps.usercontent.google.com/hostedimage/m/*/3AL_Y2X50rFNv8GVQfmRVN5rUIMI6P2rMXEIUnIJrsObsEej2YkQwSAYHiI1v94cnt_aVvPeAZON89x4u6OX_173igdoyNnjUPScIdAwKBwgs3lWhLD76daRCVj4r1SCfsz7yyCE9Y0od8b0AqP7SWOji30i5p_LNoEATU_vKIxpjJoZLqXTBfJt0M2ThiyXYs-KsQtZbqgN9?authuser=0&fife=s16383" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>London Borough of Hammersmith & Fulham, Shepherds Bush W12<br><br>In the late 1980s Shepherd's Bush like many inner-city areas saw the development of a new type of youth gang that drew membership from local estates, most notably the White City estate but also other estates including Lime Grove, Becklow Gardens and Emlyn Gardens estates, and also nearby Acton estates, such as Trinity Way estate. They were described as steaming gangs but by the early 1990s they had progressed into the drugs economy with Shepherd's Bush area seeing a number of gun killings. By the mid 1990s youth street gangs in the area had acquired a reputation for their steaming and robbery offences while the older members were inextricably linked to the drugs trade. Some of the earlier gangs growing from the mid 1990s were the 'No Face Crew', a combination of two separate gangs and the 'Borer Man Crew' from White City estate, who were mainly African, would often come into conflict with the mainly Caribbean 'Smokers Crew', based in nearby Ladbroke Grove. These conflicts were later replaced by the newer younger generations. The 'Cold Hearted Crew', from the Edward Woods estate and Shepherd's Bush based 'Urban Virus'.<br><br>The Shepherd's Bush gangs were infamously dubbed 'Rolex Robbers' soon after the millennium with the gang members taking advantage of the wealthy residences throughout the borough and nearby Kensington and Chelsea. One group of 'Rolex Robbers' foiled in 2002 were named by the media as the 'Underground G's'. Another similar style gang foiled was dubbed "Prada Mob". The most prominent Shepherds Bush gang forming around 2005/2006 a